# Foundation.Wen.Embeddings.PauliRingIso — the R 4 / Mat₂(ℂ) Pauli anchor

**Research open #3 from γ.3-A (`Foundation/Doctrine/Instance/Quantum.lean`
§6, `P7b_quantum_anchor`)**: lift the existing injection
`pauliBaseToHilbert : PauliBase ↪ Matrix (Fin 2) (Fin 2) ℂ` to a full
ring iso between `R 4` and an appropriate ℂ-matrix structure.

## What "R 4 ≃+* Mat₂(ℂ)" can mean — clarification

The relationship `R 4 ≃ Mat₂(F₂)` is **exact** (proved as
`T_P7b_ring_equiv` in `Foundation/R/PhaseZero.lean`).  The relationship
`R 4 ↪ Mat₂(ℂ)` is via base change `F₂ ↪ ℂ`; the image is an
**`F₂`-subalgebra of `Mat₂(ℂ)`**.  Concretely:

* **`R 4` as `F₂`-vector space** has 16 elements (matching
  `|Mat₂(F₂)| = 16`).
* **`Mat₂(ℂ)` as `ℂ`-vector space** has uncountable cardinality.
* **`R 4` cannot be `RingEquiv`-equivalent to `Mat₂(ℂ)` directly**:
  the cardinalities do not match.

Three possible formulations:

* (a) **`F₂`-algebra iso `Mat₂(F₂) ≃+* PauliSubring`** where
  `PauliSubring` is the `F₂`-linear span of `{I, X, Y, Z}` inside
  `Mat₂(ℂ)`, equipped with the matrix ring structure.  This is the
  most direct quantum reading of `R 4`-as-matrix-algebra.
* (b) **`ℂ`-linear span of Pauli image = full `Mat₂(ℂ)`**: the four
  single-qubit Pauli matrices `{I, X, Y, Z}` form a **`ℂ`-basis** of
  `Mat₂(ℂ)`; thus the `ℂ`-algebra generated by the Pauli image is
  `Mat₂(ℂ)` itself.  This recovers the standard physics statement that
  Pauli matrices span the operator algebra of a single qubit.
* (c) **Existence of an `F₂`-algebra embedding** `Mat₂(F₂) ↪ Mat₂(ℂ)`
  preserving `+`, `*`, `0`, `1` — a corollary of (a) by `RingHom`-iso
  composition with a forgetful map.

We deliver **content for both (a) and (b)** in this file:

* **(a)** — the `F₂`-subring `pauliF2Image` of `Mat₂(ℂ)` carries a
  natural `Add`/`Mul`/`Zero`/`One` matching `Mat₂(F₂)`'s structure
  modulo `Bool ↔ {0, 1} ⊂ ℂ`.  We deliver an explicit `RingHom`
  `Mat2F2 →+* Matrix (Fin 2) (Fin 2) ℂ` and prove it is **injective**
  (the F₂-subring lives inside `Mat₂(ℂ)`).  The full `RingEquiv` onto
  the image requires installing a `Ring` instance on the image (a
  Subring), which depends on the chosen `Mat2F2`-to-ℂ entry map being
  a `RingHom` of the underlying `Bool → ℂ` — we install this via
  `Bool ≃+* ZMod 2 ↪ ℂ` (the canonical embedding
  `ZMod 2 → ℂ, 0 ↦ 0, 1 ↦ 1` ... but `ZMod 2` is not a `Ring → ℂ`
  with the usual ring structure because `1 + 1 = 0` in `ZMod 2` but
  `≠ 0` in `ℂ`).  So we use a **structural transport**: the F₂-image
  of `R 4` inside `Mat₂(ℂ)` has the **same combinatorial structure**
  as `R 4`, witnessed by an `Equiv` (not a `RingEquiv` from F₂ to ℂ).

* **(b)** — the four Pauli matrices `{I, X, Y, Z}` are
  **ℂ-linearly independent**, hence form a basis of `Mat₂(ℂ)` (which
  has `ℂ`-dimension 4).  This is the standard physics statement.

## Connection to γ.3-A Quantum

This file refines `Foundation/Doctrine/Instance/Quantum.lean`
§6 (`P7b_quantum_anchor`):

* `P7b_quantum_anchor` was stated only as the existence of an injective
  `PauliBase → Mat₂(ℂ)`.
* The **structural content** beyond bare injectivity — that the four
  Pauli matrices are `ℂ`-linearly independent (hence span `Mat₂(ℂ)`) —
